;
; The file is generated by Kathleen Kirchner.
; Simple LJ spheres with scaled charges (1/sqrt(2)) to account polarization effects
; 
; In JPCB2008 LCr and SAr are used. 
; sigma=2*r
; r_cation=0.5nm
; r_anion=0.25nm
; epsilon=k_B * T /2
; T=450 K
;

[ atomtypes ]
;   type      mass        charge  ptype  sigma     epsilon

;name mass charge ptype c6 c12

    LC      100.80        0.707    A   10.00e-01  1.8698e+00
    SC      100.80        0.707    A   5.000e-01  1.8698e+00     
    LA      100.80       -0.707    A   10.00e-01  1.8698e+00
    MA      100.80	 -0.707    A   7.854e-01  1.8698e+00
    SA      100.80       -0.707    A   5.000e-01  1.8698e+00

    LCr     100.80        0.707    A  -10.00e-01  1.8698e+00
    SCr     100.80        0.707    A  -5.000e-01  1.8698e+00
    LAr     100.80       -0.707    A  -10.00e-01  1.8698e+00
    MAr     100.80       -0.707    A   7.854e-01  1.8698e+00
    SAr     100.80       -0.707    A  -5.000e-01  1.8698e+00

    CT      100.80        0.707    A  -10.00e-01  1.8698e+00
    AN      100.80       -0.707    A  -5.000e-01  1.8698e+00

; L = Large
; M = Medium
; S = Small
; C = Cation
; A = Anion
; r = repulsive

; Gromacs uses internal for any VdW calculations the C6-C12 form.
; When providing Lennard Jones parameter sigma and epsilon,
; Gromacs calculates C6 and C12 as follows:
;
; C6 = 4 * epsilon * sigma^6
; C12 = 4 * epsilon * sigma^12
;
; In the topology section [ defaults ] the choice of VdW potential form and combination rule is done. 
;
; [ defaults ]
; nbfunc	comb-rule	gen-pairs	fudgeLJ	fudgeQQ
; 1			1				yes		0.5		0.5 		; geometric average C6 C12
; 1			2				yes		0.5		0.5 		; arithmetic average sigma epsilon
; 1			3				yes		0.5		0.5 		; geometric average sigma epsilon (Used by OPLS-AA)
;
; In case we want or have to use combination rule 2 or 3 and thus provide Gromacs with sigma and epsilon,
; we might have trouble if our new defined potential should only have a repulsive term (C6=0).
;
; There is a trick:
; Negative Sigma sets C6 to 0 according to the developers.
;
; Source:
;
;RE: [gmx-users] C6 attractive term off OPLSAA
;Berk Hess
;Wed, 01 Dec 2010 08:06:36 -0800
;
;Hi,
;
;Maybe it is not so clear from the topology table in the manual, but when you 
;supply
;sigma and epsilon as non-bonded parameters, as for OPLS, the nonbond_params
;section also expects sigma and epsilon.
;So it seems you could not set only C6 to zero.
;However there is an, undocumented, trick: if you use a negative sigma,
;C6 is set to zero.
;
;Berk
